section.p:
FIXME: Examples with domains/regions.  transformationtransformation.
linear and squares, triangles,
z^2 and sectors.  \bar{z} and \frac{1}{z}

We say f has a complex derivativecomplex derivative L at z if

  L = \lim_{\Delta \to 0} \frac{f(z+\Delta)-f(z)}{\Delta}

Remember that \Delta is a complex number and the limit we
are taking is a complex limit.  We write f' or \frac{df}{dz}
for the derivative.

example.p:
Let's start with

  \begin{split}
  x^2-y^2+2ixy  & = 
  {\left( \frac{z+\bar{z}}{2} \right)}^2 -
  {\left( \frac{z-\bar{z}}{2i} \right)}^2 +
  2i {\left( \frac{z+\bar{z}}{2} \right)}
  {\left( \frac{z-\bar{z}}{2i} \right)}
  \\
  & =
  \cdots = z^2 .
  \end{split}

No \bar{z} anywhere in sight,
so this polynomial is analytic.

section.p:
Suppose the complex derivative of f = u+iv exists at
z=x+iy.  When we take the limit as a complex
\Delta \to 0, we might as well let it approach
along the real axis.  That is, we let \Delta = \delta,
for a real \delta:

  \begin{split}
  \Re f'(z) & =  \Re \lim_{\Delta \to 0} \frac{f(z+\Delta)-f(z)}{\Delta}
  \\
  & =
  \Re \lim_{\delta \to 0} \frac{f(z+\delta)-f(z)}{\delta}
  \\
  & =
  \lim_{\delta \to 0} \frac{u(x+\delta,y)-u(x,y)}{\delta}
  = u_x(x,y) .
  \end{split}

Next instead of letting \Delta be \delta, we let
\Delta = i \delta for a real \delta.
After all since we're allowed to approach zero in any old way,
we might as well approach along the imaginary axis now.

  \begin{split}
  \Re f'(z) & =  \Re \lim_{\Delta \to 0} \frac{f(z+\Delta)-f(z)}{\Delta}
  \\
  & =
  \Re
  \lim_{\delta \to 0} \frac{u(x,y+\delta)+iv(x,y+\delta)-u(x,y)-iv(x,y)}{i\delta}
  \\
  & =
  \lim_{\delta \to 0} \frac{v(x,y+\delta)-v(x,y)}{\delta}
  =
  v_y(x,y) .
  \end{split}

Similarly

  \begin{split}
  \Im f'(z) & =  \Im \lim_{\Delta \to 0} \frac{f(z+\Delta)-f(z)}{\Delta}
  \\
  &
  =
  \lim_{\delta \to 0} \frac{v(x+\delta,y)-v(x,y)}{\delta}
  =
  \lim_{\delta \to 0} -\frac{u(x,y+\delta)-u(x,y)}{\delta}
  \\
  & =
  v_x (x,y) = -u_y (x,y) .
  \end{split}

So if the complex derivatie exists we find

  f'(z) = u_x (x,y) + iv_x (x,y) \quad \text{and} \quad
  f'(z) = v_y (x,y) - iu_y (x,y) .

No matter, how do we compute it?
We have

  e^z = w = \abs{w}e^{i\arg w}

Taking logs we get

  \log w = \log \abs{w}e^{i\arg w}
  = (\log \abs{w}) + \log e^{i\arg w}
  = (\log \abs{w}) + i\arg w

So the multivaluedness of \log is just like the
multivaluedness of the argument.

Similarly we define so called hyperbolic trig functions

  \cosh z = \frac{e^{z} + e^{-z}}{2}
  \qquad
  \sinh z = \frac{e^{z} - e^{-z}}{2}

